Black Bess Cover GIF by Mad Monk
September 2021, 10 editions on KnownOrigin

Reimagination of the historical penny dreadful publication Black Bess' cover

Part of the Penny Dreadful Collection

...

Penny dreadfuls were cheap popular serial literature produced during the nineteenth century in the United Kingdom. The pejorative term is roughly interchangeable with penny horrible, penny awful, and penny blood. The term typically referred to a story published in weekly parts of 8 to 16 pages, each costing one penny. The subject matter of these stories was typically sensational, focusing on the exploits of detectives, criminals, or supernatural entities. First published in the 1830s, penny dreadfuls featured characters such as Sweeney Todd, Dick Turpin, Varney the Vampire and Spring-heeled Jack. (Wikipedia)

asset.name: Life Fall
asset.description:
Orfeo Tagiuris Life Fall (2021) employs hand-drawn sketches to express human mortality. Tagiuris dainty yet darkly comic diagram shows a figure endlessly falling from one man-hole marked before down through another, marked after. The empty space between is simply labelled life - putting the meme in memento mori. 

Each purchase comes with one of twenty hand drawn frames that comprise the original animation. This is a physical drawing 14x10cm signed, numbered and dated. These are unlocked using a password obtained upon purchase.

asset.description:
I was staying up late, preparing for an important speech at the meeting tomorrow. It was quite a matter of fortunes made or lost. I was not seeing straight because I thought two teeth protruding from the upper jaw. I took several steps in that direction. On the way, I tripped over a side table and fell into an armchair. All the while those Rugaj Okuloj gazing at me.."  (from the notebooks of Sir Archibald Henney)

...

asset.name: Bavaria: Kristin
asset.description:
We hoped the skies to clear. We hoped the things would not go the way they did. A little bit of cloud here and there but no rain only shadows and pain. The village was somewhat deserted. Those left behind eyed us with big suspicious eyes. The little girl with the yellow dress was in the middle of it all. The little they were all marionettes. Thus was the state of Bavaria then. That was our fate now and back then.

...

Bavaria is a project by Hulki Okan Tabak

It is inspired by the great short poem of the same name by Mary Ruefle.

It has been generated by experimentation with text inputs to the AI with relatively limited editing afterwards.

The pieces of the collection will start to be minted on KnownOrigin as of January 2022. The plan is to mint the artwork set as multi editions but some items could be 1/1s if there is demand.

At the maximum there are 21 still images and 4 moving ones in the collection.

They have been named and are ready to be minted now.

asset.name: Stitch Bunny Genesis Fire Edition 2021 Sabet
asset.description:
This is the first Stitch Bunny released into the wild. He will be the most famous bunny in the NFT world and I can't wait to share more of him with you all!

Stitch is all love. hes open and friendly. He is highly intelligent, and happy most of the time. He can get real down on himself and that really messes up his forward movement. But when hes on, there is no stopping him. He helps all his friends at every level. His open heart and gullibleness gets him in trouble, but love always prevails.

Pixopop is the manifestation of love through the characters of award-winning designer and illustrator Ali Sabet. Born in Iran and raised in California, Ali founded Sabet Brands in 1999, a full service branding agency that to this day helps create some of the most powerful brands in the world. Ali has loved characters for as long as he can remember. Theyve inspired him, made him smile and sparked his imagination. He's always dreamed of creating characters that would bring the same emotion and joy to the life of others. It took him 12 years of constant evolution to bring to life the characters that fulfill his purpose, and that today genuinely inspire a large and loyal audience.

more on www.pixopop.com

asset.name: Uncertainty Principle
asset.description: The principle in quantum theory, formulated by Werner Heisenberg in 1926, which holds that the values of certain pairs of variables cannot BOTH be known exactly, so that the more precisely one variable is known, the less precisely the other can be known. For example, if the speed or momentum of a particle is known exactly, then its location must remain uncertain; if its location is known with certainty, then the particles speed or momentum cannot be known. Formulated another way, relating the uncertainties of energy and time, the uncertainty principle permits the existence of ultra-short-lived microscopic particles (virtual particles) in apparently empty space, which briefly blink into existence and blink out again.

Spring Heeled Jack Cover GIF by Mad Monk

October 2021, 10 editions on KnownOrigin

Part of the Penny Dreadful Collection

...

Penny dreadfuls were cheap popular serial literature produced during the nineteenth century in the United Kingdom. The pejorative term is roughly interchangeable with penny horrible, penny awful, and penny blood. The term typically referred to a story published in weekly parts of 8 to 16 pages, each costing one penny. The subject matter of these stories was typically sensational, focusing on the exploits of detectives, criminals, or supernatural entities. First published in the 1830s, penny dreadfuls featured characters such as Sweeney Todd, Dick Turpin, Varney the Vampire and Spring-heeled Jack. (Wikipedia)

asset.name: Rugaj Okuloj
asset.description:
I was staying up late, preparing for an important speech at the meeting tomorrow. It was quite a matter of fortunes made or lost. Anxiously fumbling after a couple of drinks, I noticed the pair of red eyes glinting in the dimly lit corner of the study. Perched above was a symbol I was unable to decipher due to my intoxication. Most of the face seemed unrecognizable anyhow. Covered by the shadows. The mouth was stern. Unbreakable jaw I thought, unbelievably unbreakable. I was not seeing straight because I thought two teeth protruding from the upper jaw. I took several steps in that direction. On the way, I tripped over a side table and fell into an armchair. All the while those Rugaj Okuloj gazing at me.."  (from the notebooks of Sir Archibald Henney)

...

This artwork is part of Project F. So what does F stand for? Is it one word? Is it a heading under which various Fs reside? Female? Fun? Fate? Fortuna?

asset.name: Old Bones
asset.description:
This was my first drawing that started the 30min Sketches series- #1. This drawing is inspired by the Capuching Crypt.

Once as a kid I got lost for a few minutes in a crypt and it left a strong impression on me. That crypt was more like an underground maze with lots of candles, paintings and glass coffins. Those few minutes felt much longer, the dark tight tunnels felt endless, every turn I wondered what I'd see next, how long till find a way out. Once I found my group I felt relief, but also regret that it was over so soon; no one noticed. 
I love happy fantasy, but I'm also drawn to the scary and slightly morbid art, especially with various mysteries. Sometimes skulls make me uneasy, but they're also fascinating because they're left behind by various lives we might never truly know about. 
The awareness that everything ends can be debilitating but also motivating, we want to be remembered. These sketches are my way of expressing myself more instead of just daydreaming as before.

asset.name: Descent to Madness
asset.description:
Descent to Madness by Hulki Okan Tabak

Mass Limited Edition of 25, Minted April 2021 on KnownOrigin

...

Descent to Madness is the most openly disturbing Nussbaum interpretation I've created. It's based on two Nussbaum paintings with the one in the background providing the setting for the descending front image. Each image was altered individually and merged in a psycho glitch GIF. I have no cheer up words for the message. And yes there is a message. And no it still is individually discoverable but mutually carried on the shoulders of all.

As part of a series, it is a piece built upon the various works of the Jewish surrealist painter Felix Nussbaum. He was born 1904 in Osnabruck and died 1944 with his wife, in the Auschwitz concentration camp. As of 2015, Nussbaum's work entered public domain.
